Improvement summary: use `ClassPathXmlApplicationContext` (so the XML at `com/nt/cfgs/applicationContext.xml` is loaded from the classpath), use typed `getBean(...)`, and try-with-resources to auto-close the context. This is more robust and concise.

```java
// File: src/com/nt/main/DependencyManagementTest.java
package com.nt.main;

import org.springframework.context.support.ClassPathXmlApplicationContext;
import com.nt.sbeans.WishMessageGenerator;

public class DependencyManagementTest {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try (ClassPathXmlApplicationContext ctx =
                 new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("com/nt/cfgs/applicationContext.xml")) {
            WishMessageGenerator generator = ctx.getBean("wmg", WishMessageGenerator.class);
            String result = generator.showWishMessage("raja");
            System.out.println(result);
        }
    }
}
```

Brief diagnosis:
- `WishMessageGenerator.java` and `WishMessageGemerater/src/com/nt/cfgs/applicationContext.xml` look correct: bean id `ltime` and property `time` match the `setTime(LocalTime)` setter.
- The likely error is how the XML is loaded. `new FileSystemXmlApplicationContext("src/com/nt/cfgs/applicationContext.xml")` often fails at runtime because the classpath resource is different in Eclipse. Use `ClassPathXmlApplicationContext` with the classpath location `com/nt/cfgs/applicationContext.xml`, or fix the filesystem path to the actual file location.

Fixed `DependencyManagementTest.java` (uses classpath, typed `getBean`, try-with-resources):

